diff:1620522406:1619293436:=48,59c48%0a%3c #foxbegin 210509-010647-405100#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!![l] and [n] are indeed not used in some Chinese dialects %0a%3c -> - Simon_Y%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Just wanted to mention that there are some dialects of Chinese that do not use [l] and [n] contrastively. For example, Hubei's dialect doesn't. I would suspect that of the limited number of Chinese speakers that the author of the post has interacted with, he/she has probably interacted with one who speaks those dialects. %0a%3c %0a%3c Ironically, the incredibly descriptive view of the author does not really answer the question. "Do Chinese know better English than Indian?" is this question asking about the average level in English in these countries? Or whether if there is one nationality with some kind of inherent limit? The author never clarified. The former can be answered more unbiasedly and has more to do with the international/cultural influence of the country. But the latter is just discriminatory, but sadly it has earned its popularity online.%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210509-010647-405100#%0a---%0a> %0a
